{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01FCAAH7DqmvCFFqP4wGsUmK","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# onclustertesting\n2\t\n3\t## Overview\n4\t\n5\tProvides a very simple binary for setting up / tearing down on-cluster layering\n6\tto make testing / development go faster.\n7\t\n8\t## Prerequisites\n9\t- An OpenShift cluster running 4.16+\n10\t- Kubeconfig for the aforementioned cluster\n11\t- OpenShift CLI (`oc`)\n12\t- _(optional, but recommended)_ [K9s](https://k9scli.io/)\n13\t\n14\t## Usage\n15\t\n16\t### Setup\n17\t\n18\tOnce you've installed the binary, you can set up a simple on-cluster layering\n19\ttesting situation which makes use of some handy defaults such as using the\n20\tglobal pull secret and an in-cluster OpenShift ImageStream for pushing the\n21\tbuilt image to.\n22\t\n23\tTo do this, run:\n24\t`$ onclustertesting setup in-cluster-registry --enable-feature-gate --pool=layered`\n25\t\n26\tUnder the hood, this will perform the following actions:\n27\t1. Verify that the appropriate feature gate is enabled, and enable it if desired.\n28\t2. Create an ImageStream within the MCO namespace called `os-image`.\n29\t3. Create a MachineConfigPool to target (defaults to `layered`) and waits for it to get an initial MachineConfig (this wait does not block the other operations, with the exception of creating a MachineOSConfig).\n30\t4. Clones the global pull secret into the MCO namespace.\n31\t5. Creates additional secrets / ConfigMaps as needed (see Other Features section below for more details). If a ConfigMap or Secret was previously created by the `onclustertesting` tool, it will be deleted and recreated.\n32\t6. Creates a MachineOSConfig for the newly-created pool once the new MachineConfigPool has an initial config, optionally adding a custom Containerfile to it.\n33\t7. The MCO should start the `machine-os-builder` pod and the build will begin. Note: `onclustertesting` will not wait for the build to complete before it exits. So you may want to use something like [K9s](https://k9scli.io/) to watch its progress.\n34\t\n35\tThis setup will use the in-cluster registry which requires no external\n36\tcredentials to be used. The pool will start building as soon as it can. Note:\n37\tIf the `TechPreviewNoUpgrade` feature gate was not previously enabled, this\n38\twill create a new MachineConfig in all MachineConfigPools, incurring a full\n39\tMachineConfig rollout before the build will start.\n40\t\n41\tAll objects created by the `onclustertesting` tool include the label\n42\t`machineconfiguration.openshift.io/createdByOnClusterBuildsHelper`. This\n43\tallows the tool to completely remove any and all objects that it created during\n44\tthe teardown phase.\n45\t\n46\t### Teardown\n47\t\n48\tAssuming you have not applied any built images to your cluster nodes, one can\n49\teasily teardown everything set up by `onclustertesting` just by running the `$\n50\tonclustertesting teardown` command.\n51\t\n52\tThis will do the following:\n53\t1. Delete any ConfigMaps or Secrets created by the `onclustertesting` tool.\n54\t2. Delete all build objects created by the `machine-os-builder` process, including any running build pods, ConfigMaps, Secrets, etc.\n55\t3. Delete all MachineConfigPools created by the `onclustertesting` tool.\n56\t4. Delete all MachineConfigs applied to the MachineConfigPool(s) created by the `onclustertesting` tool.\n57\t5. Delete all MachineOSBuild objects.\n58\t6. Delete all MachineOSConfig objects.\n59\t7. Delete all ImageStreams created by the `onclustertesting` tool.\n60\t\n61\t### Rollouts\n62\t\n63\tBy itself, `onclustertesting` will only test the build and push phases of the\n64\ton-cluster layering process.\n65\t\n66\tTo test the rollout process (applying the newly-built image to a node), you'll\n67\tneed to move a given node into the MachineConfigPool created by the\n68\t`onclustertesting` program. One can do that by running the following command:\n69\t\n70\t`$ onclustertesting optin --pool=<desired pool> --node=<desired node>`\n71\t\n72\tThere is also an optout helper that performs the inverse operation:\n73\t\n74\t`$ onclustertesting optout --pool=<desired pool> --node=<desired node>`\n75\t\n76\tAlternatively, you can use `oc` or `kubectl` to perform the same action:\n77\t\n78\t`$ oc label node/<desired-node> -l 'node-role.kubernetes.io/<name-of-machineconfigpool>='`\n79\t\n80\tIt is worth mentioning that once a node is opted in, using `onclustertesting`'s\n81\tteardown process may leave your cluster in a difficult-to-recover-from state.\n82\tThis is mostly because the revert feature does not work yet. Once that is\n83\tfeature is implemented in OCL, this should no longer be a problem.\n84\t\n85\t## Other features\n86\t\n87\t### RHEL entitlements\n88\t\n89\tIf your cluster has the `etc-pki-entitlement` secret in the\n90\t`openshift-config-managed` namespace, the operator will automatically\n91\tcopy it into the MCO namespace, when a build is required.\n92\t\n93\t### /etc/yum.repos.d and /etc/pki/rpm-gpg\n94\t\n95\tIf you want to test the `/etc/yum.repos.d` and `/etc/pki/rpm-gpg` injection\n96\tcapabilities of on-cluster layering, you can provide the `--inject-yum-repos`\n97\tflag with the `setup` command. Doing this will cause the following to occur:\n98\t\n99\t1. `onclustertesting` will use the `oc`\n100\tcommand to extract the `/etc/yum.repos.d` and `/etc/pki/rpm-gpg` directories\n101\tfrom a container image found at `quay.io/zzlotnik/devex:epel`. For speed, this\n102\timage only contains those directories and is built using [this\n103\tContainerfile](https://github.com/cheesesashimi/containerfiles/commit/33ddc71dc3f480055cfb41f3c6a568c70d4d81da#diff-79251285e7d83f5a8acf208fdb543c6f7ac5c2af3d533cb0458d6c4010a5d4d3).\n104\t2. These files will be placed in a temporary directory before being converted into a ConfigMap and Secret.\n105\t3. The ConfigMap `etc-yum-repos-d` and the Secret `etc-pki-rpm-gpg` will be created within the MCO namespace.\n106\t4. The temporary directory will be removed.\n107\t\n108\tThese objects will be removed during the teardown process.\n109\t\n110\t### Custom Containerfiles\n111\t\n112\tDuring the setup process, you can optionally inject a custom Containerfile by\n113\tsupplying the `--containerfile-path` flag and a path to a Containerfile present on\n114\tyour machine.\n115\t\n116\tThe Containerfile will be read and injected into the MachineOSConfig for the\n117\tMachineConfigPool that the tool creates.\n118\t\n119\t**Note:** The custom Containerfile must include a stage beginning with `FROM\n120\tconfigs AS final` in order for your customizations to be built into the final image.\n121\t\n122\t### CI mode\n123\t\n124\tCI mode is a new subcommand under the `setup` command, which is intended to opt\n125\ta given cluster into on-cluster layering so that a test suite (such as\n126\t`openshift-e2e`) may be run against it. Using this command does the following:\n127\t\n128\t1. Creates two ImageStreams; one for the control-plane and one for the worker pool.\n129\t2. Clones the global pull secret into the MCO namespace.\n130\t3. Creates a MachineOSConfig for both the control-plane and worker pool. Then waits for the builds to complete.\n131\t4. Waits for the newly-built image to roll out to each node in both the control-plane and worker pools.\n132\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_014NA5Hm4ucczaQabTwCT8iW","session_id":"e75a21bc-7faa-413c-8450-02eaf032edac","uuid":"53d89d05-02c8-44eb-b754-1a43230343c6","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:07:39.029Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Search for MachineOSConfig and on-cluster layering docs"}
