{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01DnZR1Z6x89bUEsjjsRz2mP","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Machine OS Builder Design\n2\t\n3\tIn the context of the Machine Config Operator (MCO) in Red Hat\n4\tOpenShift, on-cluster builds refer to the process of building an OS\n5\timage directly on the OpenShift cluster, rather than building them\n6\toutside the cluster (such as on a local machine or continuous\n7\tintegration (CI) pipeline) and then making a configuration change so\n8\tthat the cluster uses them. By doing this, we enable cluster\n9\tadministrators to have more control over the contents and configuration\n10\tof their clusters’ OS image through a familiar interface (MachineConfigs\n11\tand in the future, Dockerfiles).\n12\t\n13\t![MOB Diagram](./MachineOSBuilderDiagram.svg)\n14\t\n15\t## Sub-components and design\n16\t\n17\tOn-cluster builds are achieved with the help of several subcomponents\n18\tthat work in concert with one another. This is a brief overview of what\n19\tthey do and how they work:\n20\t\n21\t### Machine OS Builder (MOB)\n22\t\n23\tThis is an additional binary which forms a part of the Machine Config\n24\tOperator. By implementing as much of the on-cluster build functionality\n25\twithin the MOB binary, we can ensure that the code paths are only\n26\treached whenever a cluster admin explicitly opts into OS layering. This\n27\ttop-level component (and its subcomponents described below) is only\n28\tstarted whenever a cluster administrator opts in. If a cluster\n29\tadministrator opts out, it will gracefully shut down. The below\n30\tsubcomponents (BuildController, ImageBuildController,\n31\tPodBuildController) are part of the MOB binary.\n32\t\n33\t### BuildController\n34\t\n35\tBuildController is the entrypoint for determining whenever an OS build\n36\tis required as well as ingesting the user-provided configuration details\n37\t(described below). BuildController listens for changes to\n38\tMachineConfigPools and determines whether a change requires a new OS\n39\timage build. At the time of this writing, only a rendered MachineConfig\n40\tchange will cause a new build to be performed. Other changes to\n41\tMachineConfigPools will be ignored at this time. It is worth noting that\n42\tBuildController only determines whether a build is needed, makes the\n43\tnecessary preparations, starts the build, and updates the\n44\tMachineConfigPool with the current build state. Upon completion, it will\n45\tretrieve the image pullspec from the build process and update the\n46\tMachineConfigPool object with the latest image pullspec.\n47\t\n48\tTo actually perform the build, BuildController makes use of either the\n49\tImageBuildController or the PodBuildController as described below. It is\n50\timportant to understand that ImageBuildController and PodBuildController\n51\tare designed to be as interchangeable as possible. Additional image\n52\tbuilders may be produced in the future to support additional use-cases\n53\tand to optimize the build process within certain OpenShift contexts\n54\t(e.g., single-node). However for now, we have the two described below.\n55\t\n56\t### ImageBuildController\n57\t\n58\tImageBuildController makes use of the OpenShift Image Builder\n59\tfunctionality which is currently a core feature of OpenShift. When this\n60\tfeature is present on ones’ OpenShift cluster, BuildController will\n61\tstart an ImageBuildController which creates an OpenShift Build object to\n62\tperform the build. Because OpenShift Image Builder will eventually\n63\tbecome an optional component, it makes sense that we should have a\n64\tsecond mechanism for clusters which do not have the OpenShift Image\n65\tBuilder capability enabled. Using OpenShift Image Builder allows us to\n66\tavoid implementing this specific functionality itself and has the\n67\tadditional benefit that the OpenShift Image Builder components are\n68\tlifecycled and versioned along with the rest of the OpenShift release\n69\tprocess.\n70\t\n71\t### PodBuildController\n72\t\n73\tPodBuildController enables builds by creating a custom build pod, which\n74\tuses the officially published Buildah image\n75\t(`quay.io/buildah/stable:latest`). Additionally, PodBuildController\n76\tattempts to run with the fewest privileges possible. To do so, the\n77\t`machine-os-builder` service account (which MOB runs as) sets the `anyuid`\n78\tSecurity Context Constraint. This allows us to map the build UID\n79\tcontained within the Buildah container to a UID on our cluster,\n80\teffectively allowing us to run as an unprivileged pod, without root"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_014NA5Hm4ucczaQabTwCT8iW","session_id":"e75a21bc-7faa-413c-8450-02eaf032edac","uuid":"e76184b7-7ac1-4a94-ac47-677c2f59db1a","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:08:14.696Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Search for MachineOSConfig and on-cluster layering docs"}
